, antennal spine; 
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076AFFF1119105CBFD22A8F7" bold="true" box="[687,698,1985,2002]" pageId="18" pageNumber="41">b</emphasis>
, antennal groove; 
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076AFFF1106A05CBFCFFA8F0" bold="true" box="[852,871,1985,2005]" pageId="18" pageNumber="41">
b 
<subScript id="3D5834DA076AFFF1105E05C3FCFFA8F0" attach="right" box="[864,871,1993,2005]" fontSize="5" pageId="18" pageNumber="41">1</subScript>
</emphasis>
, hepatic groove; 
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076AFFF110C905CBFB9AA8F7" bold="true" box="[1015,1026,1985,2002]" pageId="18" pageNumber="41">c</emphasis>
, postcervical; 
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076AFFF1174405CBFB1DA8F7" bold="true" box="[1146,1157,1985,2002]" pageId="18" pageNumber="41">d</emphasis>
, gastro-orbital groove; 
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076AFFF1167705CBFAFEA8F7" bold="true" box="[1353,1382,1985,2005]" pageId="18" pageNumber="41">
e 
<subScript id="3D5834DA076AFFF1166D05C3FAC2A8F0" attach="both" box="[1363,1370,1993,2005]" fontSize="5" pageId="18" pageNumber="41">1</subScript>
e
</emphasis>
, cervical groove; 
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076AFFF113F605D2FF40A8CC" bold="true" box="[200,216,2008,2025]" pageId="18" pageNumber="41">ip</emphasis>
, intercalated plate. Black arrows show the spines. Photographs and line drawings: J. Devillez. Scale bars: 1 cm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="A163369F076BFFF013BA02DDFE3DAE14" blockId="19.[130,778,215,306]" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">straight or slightly curved inward, with a terminal hook; occlusal margin without teeth; P1 carpus short, subtriangular; thin P2-P5; P2-P3 chelate.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A163369F076BFFF013BA0352FEBEAE57" blockId="19.[132,294,344,370]" box="[132,294,344,370]" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">
<heading id="FA2B81F3076BFFF013BA0352FEBEAE57" box="[132,294,344,370]" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" reason="8">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF013BA0352FEBEAE57" box="[132,294,344,370]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">Ornamentation</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A163369F076BFFF013BA0373FE4BAD16" blockId="19.[130,777,377,563]" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">Carapace with a dense, heterogeneous ornamentation; gastric and cardiac regions covered by tubercles; antennal, hepatic, and branchial regions covered by small rounded depressions; presence of an orbital spine; tergites and pleurites densely covered by small rounded depressions; presence of a strong antennal spine; smooth P1-P5.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9C66514076BFFF013BA0050FD0DAA51" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A163369F076BFFF013BA0050FE9EAD57" blockId="19.[130,777,602,1396]" box="[132,262,602,628]" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">DISCUSSION</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A163369F076BFFF013BA0070FEA2AC71" blockId="19.[130,777,602,1396]" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">
This species is only known by three specimens. It is assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF0139E0091FF7CAD91" authorityName="Meyer" authorityYear="1840" box="[160,228,667,692]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF0139E0091FF7CAD91" box="[160,228,667,692]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">Eryma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of its typical carapace groove pattern (short gastro-orbital groove, postcervical and branchiocardiac grooves joined at carapace mid-height, hepatic groove concavo-convex) and the shape of the P1 chelae (elongated propodus, subrectangular, with slender fingers progressively narrowing to their distal extremity).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A163369F076BFFF013A50151FE7AAB51" blockId="19.[130,777,602,1396]" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">
Among the erymid lobsters, 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF012E50151FD13AC51" authorityName="Schweigert, Dietl &amp; Roper" authorityYear="2000" box="[475,651,858,884]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westphali">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF012E50151FD13AC51" box="[475,651,858,884]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">Eryma westphali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only species with heterochelous P1 chelae on a same specimen. Left propodus is more elongated and narrower than the right one, and the left fingers are straight and short while the right ones are curved and slightly longer (
<figureCitation id="39E72A1A076BFFF0113401D0FDF4ACD0" box="[522,620,986,1013]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="18.[132,143,1894,1911]" captionTargetBox="[132,1455,215,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-28@18.[698,1267,769,1326]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIG. 7. — Eryma major Oppel, 1861, Eryma veltheimii (Münster, 1839) and Eryma westphali Schweigert, Dietl &amp; Röper, 2000 from the Kimmeridgian of Germany: A, holotype SMNS 3682 of E. major from Egesheimer;B, specimen SMNS 67655 of E. major from Gerhausen; C, specimen SMNS 64371 of E. major from Nusplingen; D-F, holotype BSPG AS VII 186 of E. veltheimii from Kehlheim: part (D), counter-part (E), details of telson and uropods (F); G-J, holotype SMNS 24227 of E. westphali from Nusplingen: general view (G), schema of the carapace (H), schema of left chela (I), schema of right chela (J); C, specimen SMNS 63733 from Nusplingen. Abbreviations: a, branchiocardiac; as, antennal spine; b, antennal groove; b1, hepatic groove; c, postcervical; d, gastro-orbital groove; e1e, cervical groove; ip, intercalated plate. Black arrows show the spines. Photographs and line drawings: J. Devillez. Scale bars: 1 cm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4486491" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4486491/files/figure.png" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">Fig. 7I, J</figureCitation>
). The strongly elongated and narrow P1 propodus with relatively short fingers of 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF013CB0611FEEDAB11" authorityName="Schweigert, Dietl &amp; Roper" authorityYear="2000" box="[245,373,1050,1076]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westphali">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF013CB0611FEEDAB11" box="[245,373,1050,1076]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. westphali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characteristic of the species. Only 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF013B80630FE6AAB71" authority="(Munster, 1839)" baseAuthorityName="Munster" baseAuthorityYear="1839" box="[134,498,1082,1108]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="veltheimii">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF013B80630FEAFAB71" box="[134,311,1082,1108]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">Eryma veltheimii</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="C54D4B6E076BFFF012790630FE72AB71" author="MUNSTER G. &amp; GRAF ZU" box="[327,490,1082,1108]" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref34482" refString="MUNSTER G. &amp; GRAF ZU 1839. - Decapoda Macrura. Abbildung und Beschreibung der Fossilen langschwanzigen Krebse in den Kalkschiefern von Bayern. Beitrage zur Petrefaktenkunde 2: 1 - 88." type="journal article" year="1839">Münster, 1839</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
have P1 with a very long propodus, but it is clearly wider.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A163369F076BFFF013A50671FD0DAA51" blockId="19.[130,777,602,1396]" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">
In 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF013860671FEADABB1" authorityName="Schweigert, Dietl &amp; Roper" authorityYear="2000" box="[184,309,1146,1172]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westphali">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF013860671FEADABB1" box="[184,309,1146,1172]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. westphali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the branchial region is dorsally shorter than in 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF0139A0691FE8BAB91" box="[164,275,1179,1204]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="georgeii">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF0139A0691FE8BAB91" box="[164,275,1179,1204]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. georgeii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF0121D0691FE33AB91" authorityName="Feldmann &amp; Titus" authorityYear="2006" box="[291,427,1179,1204]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jungostrix">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF0121D0691FE33AB91" box="[291,427,1179,1204]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. jungostrix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF012820691FD8AAB91" baseAuthorityName="Etallon" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[444,530,1178,1204]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lerasi">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF012820691FD8AAB91" box="[444,530,1178,1204]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. lerasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF0111C0691FD56AB91" baseAuthorityName="Schlotheim" baseAuthorityYear="1822" box="[546,718,1178,1204]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="modestiforme">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF0111C0691FD56AB91" box="[546,718,1178,1204]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. modestiforme</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF013B806B1FE93ABF1" authorityName="Erymoidea" baseAuthorityName="Meyer" baseAuthorityYear="1835" box="[134,267,1211,1236]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ventrosum">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF013B806B1FE93ABF1" box="[134,267,1211,1236]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. ventrosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Contrary to 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF012A006B1FE68ABF1" baseAuthorityName="Etallon" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[414,496,1210,1236]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lerasi">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF012A006B1FE68ABF1" box="[414,496,1210,1236]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. lerasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF0111B06B1FD67ABF1" authorityName="Trautschold" authorityYear="1866" box="[549,767,1210,1236]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadriverrucatum">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF0111B06B1FD67ABF1" box="[549,767,1210,1236]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. quadriverrucatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF013BA06D1FE9CABD1" authorityName="Schweigert, Dietl &amp; Roper" authorityYear="2000" box="[132,260,1242,1268]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westphali">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF013BA06D1FE9CABD1" box="[132,260,1242,1268]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. westphali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
exhibits a ventral extension of the postcervical groove. Moreover, the dichotomy of the ornamentation of the carapace between the gastric and cardiac regions, covered by tubercles, and the remaining regions of 
<taxonomicName id="66DC4D1C076BFFF011140731FD3FAA71" authorityName="Schweigert, Dietl &amp; Roper" authorityYear="2000" box="[554,679,1338,1364]" class="Malacostraca" family="Erymidae" genus="Eryma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="19" pageNumber="42" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="westphali">
<emphasis id="93A8EA8D076BFFF011140731FD3FAA71" box="[554,679,1338,1364]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="42">E. westphali</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, covered by small depressions, is unique among the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
